Reframe Loreglide as a tray-resident background service

- Global watch (OS-wide UIA/AX) is now the primary mode. The in-window
  editor has been demoted to a small collapsible "test box" that is
  clearly labeled as a TTS smoke test, not a workspace.
- Watcher now takes a callback and emits `loreglide:spoke` IPC events so
  the control panel can show a live "LAST HEARD" readout with the kind
  (word / sentence), text, and age in seconds.
- System tray icon installed via TrayIconBuilder with a Show / Pause /
  Quit menu. Left-clicking the icon toggles the window.
- Close-to-tray: WindowEvent::CloseRequested is intercepted so the X
  button hides the window instead of quitting. Only the tray's Quit
  menu actually exits the process.
- Privacy: UIA probe skips any focused element whose IsPassword
  property is true, so login dialogs and credential fields are never
  read aloud.
- Added LOREGLIDE_AUTO_WATCH=1 env var to boot with the watcher
  pre-enabled for scripted end-to-end tests. Verified by typing into a
  WinForms TextBox in a separate process and observing
  speak Word("hello"), speak Word("world"), and
  speak Sentence(...) events firing in real time.
- UI: redesigned App.tsx / App.css around a black/white brutalist hero
  that inverts when the service is listening, with explicit
  LISTENING / PAUSED / UNAVAILABLE status. README updated to match the
  new mental model.
